    Direct replication attempt to evaluate a claim from Lee_EvoHumanBehavior_2018_AvWY
Replication team: Szumowska Ewa, Czernatowicz-Kukuczka Aneta
SCORE RR ID: 8g91
OSF Project: https://osf.io/uyt9p
Instructions
For each claim that you are evaluating in this data-analytic replication attempt, please complete all sections below. Please feel free to remove these and the other instructions for the final report that you provide on OSF.
Each claim evaluation must include a binary determination of whether or not the claim was replicated, given the inferential criteria. In other words, a sentence along the lines of “This claim [was/was not] replicated.” should appear in every claim evaluation. You can (and should!) also articulate in your discussion why this interpretation may be limited, but programmatic requirements of the SCORE project at large include the binary decision so it must be present.
There are also specific requirements for reporting the results of inferential tests:
Any p-value should be reported as an exact value, not a threshold, e.g.“p = .047” rather than “p < .05”. Please also indicate whether it is from a one- or two-tailed test.
Report the full text of your results with as much precision as possible. For example, a satisfactory report for the focal coefficient might be “unstandardized OLS coefficient for income term = 0.342367” vs an unsatisfactory report of “beta = 0.34”.
Please verify that for any test that was used as the basis for a power analysis, you are reporting the same effect size type used in that power analysis. It may not be the same type of effect size as was reported in the original paper (e.g., we convert to Cohen’s f squared to power many regression analyses, which is not commonly reported).
For any test that does not have a corresponding power analysis, please provide an effect size that corresponds to one from the original paper to the extent possible.
In the case of a regression analysis, please report the most unstandardized coefficient possible, e.g., the log-odds instead of the odds ratio. You may also report standardized values.
If there are multiple cells/conditions or levels to your analysis, please provide the sample sizes for each cell or level, e.g., “234823 participants nested within 32 countries” or “angry condition n = 83, happy condition n = 85”.
If multiple claims are evaluated using the same model, it is ok to group them together. In that case, please ensure that it is still clear which specific test/coefficient corresponds to which claim ID, and that there is still an evaluation of whether each claim replicated or not.
Scientific notation is acceptable for especially small or large values.
These requirements apply to all “simple” tests (one inferential test expected to be significant) and any inferential test contained within a “complex” test of a claim.
If applicable, please also distinguish which results come from an analysis of (a) entirely new data, (b) “hybrid” data (composed of both data that was used in the original study and new data), and/or (c) entirely original data.
Description of generalizability
[Please describe how this study departs from the original study, and how it speaks to the original claim(s).]

The study did not substantially deviate from the original one, except for the fact that all study materials was translated into Polish. Moreover, at the end of the study additional six-item questionnaire of quest for significance (Molinario et al., 2022) was applied. The questionnaire was administered after completing the main study (before debriefing), therefore it could not affect the results in any way. 
Despite a larger sample, the gender balance between the conditions was analogous to the original study. 
Claim evaluation
Single-trace claim
Coded claim 4 text (original paper): “Most importantly, we found a significant interaction effect between the group and dilemma type, F(1.742, 80.11) = 4.779, p = .014, partial eta squared = 0.094”
This claim was not replicated. 
Replication outcome: Simple test
Inferential criteria: Criteria for a successful replication attempt for the SCORE project is a statistically significant effect (alpha = .05, two tailed) in the same pattern as the original study on the focal statistical evidence above. For this study a successful replication requires a significant group (observed vs control) by type of dilemma interaction. 
Result:
Description of the sample
160 participants took part in the study (76 Females, 77 Males, 4 non-binary, 2 other, one person did not report gender; Mage=23.03, SD=4.95).  The structure of education in the sample was as follows: 1 Elementary, 3 Secondary, 119 currently studying, 32 Tertiary, 5 people did not report their education level. 
4 participants (1F, 3M; two from each condition) were excluded from the main analysis as due to technical issues they did not provide answers for the moral dilemmas in the main task. 
The assumed target analytic sample size was 144 participants; therefore, we met the criteria stated in the preregistration protocol. 
Moral dilemmas: Proportion of deontological responses
The 2 (group) × 3 (dilemma type) mixed ANOVA on the proportion of deontological responses revealed a significant simple effect of dilemma type, F(1.820, 280.208)= 415.008, p< .001, η2p=0.729. Bonferroni-corrected multiple comparisons found that the personal moral dilemmas produced more deontological responses (M=0.6388, SD=0.1582) than both impersonal moral dilemmas (M=0.5124, SD=0.1182) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[0.095, 0.158]) and non-moral dilemmas (M=0.2739, SD=0.0663) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[0.330, 0.400]).Participants were also more likely to make deontological decisions in impersonal moral dilemmas vs. non-moral dilemmas (p<0.001, 95%CI=[0.212, 0.265]). 
There was no significant effect of group on moral decisions F(1,154)=1.003, p=0.318, η2p=0.006.
Crucially, however, we did not find significant interaction between the condition and the type of dilemma F(1.820, 280.208)=0.237, p=0.768, η2p=0.002. The interaction remained insignificant after controlling for the participants’ baseline moral orientation (D-parameter), F=(1.860,284.626)=0.224, p=0.783, η2p=0.001. 
Moral dilemmas: Decision confidence
The 2 (group) × 3 (dilemma type) × 2 (response type) mixed ANOVA on the decision confidence yielded a significant main effect of dilemma type, F(1.905,293.360)= 79.009, p< .001, η2p= 0.339. Participants generally indicated the lower decision confidence for the judgments in personal moral dilemmas (M= 1.450 ± 0.014) vs. impersonal moral dilemmas  (M= 1.502 ± 0.015) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-0.084, -0.019]), personal  moral  dilemmas  vs.  non-moral  dilemmas (M= 1.635 ± 0.017) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-0.224, -0.145]) and  impersonal  moral  dilemmas  vs.  non-moral  dilemmas (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-0.171, -0.09]).
There was no significant effect of response type F(1,154)=2.444, p=0.123, η2p=0.016. 
There was no significant effect of group, F(1,154)=0.533, p=0.467, η2p=0.003. 
The interaction between Response Type and Group was nonsignificant F(1,154)=0.373, p=0.542, η2p=0.002. 
The interaction between Dilemma type and Response Type was significant F(1.910, 294.113)=353.087, p<0.001, η2p=0.696. For the response Appropriate participants were less confident in the personal moral dilemmas (M=1.234 ± 0.020) as compared to non-personal moral dilemmas (M=1.490 ± 0.019) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-0.306, -0.206]), as well as non-moral dilemmas (M=1.835 ± 0.014) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-0.653, -0.549]). Moreover, for the response Appropriate participants were less confident in the non-personal moral dilemmas as compared to non-moral dilemmas (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-0.391, -0.2959). For the response Inappropriate participants were more confident in the personal moral dilemmas (M=1.667 ± 0.014) as compared to non-personal moral dilemmas (M=1.515 ± 0.018) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[0.110, 0.195]), as well as non-moral dilemmas (M=1.435 ± 0.026) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[0.172, 0.293]). Moreover, for the response Inappropriate participants were more confident in the non-personal moral dilemmas as compared to non-moral dilemmas (p=0.007, 95%CI=[0.017, 0.142]).
The interaction between Dilemma Type and Group was nonsignificant F(1.905,154)=0.214, p=0.807, η2p=0.001. 
The tree-way interaction between Group, Response Type and Dilemma Type was also nonsignificant F(1.910, 294.113)=1.041, p=0.354, η2p=0.007.
Moral dilemmas: Reaction time
The 2 (group) × 3 (dilemma type) × 2 (response type) mixed ANOVA on reaction times yielded a significant main effect of dilemma type, F(1.759,153.00)= 118.285, p< 0.001, η2p= 0.436. Participants generally had longer reaction time for the judgments in non-moral moral dilemmas (M= 6.640 ± 0.150) vs. personal moral dilemmas  (M=5.084 ± 0.149) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[1.173, 1.933]), non-moral  dilemmas  vs.  non-personal  dilemmas (M=4.686 ± 0.099) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[1.666, 2.243]). Moreover participants took more time to make a decision in personal moral dilemmas as compared to non-personal dilemmas (p=0.004, 95%CI=[0.103, 0.700]).
There was marginally significant effect of response type, F(1,153)=3.880, p=0.051, η2p=0.025. It took longer for participants to answer Inappropriate (M=5.582 ± 0.116) than Appropriate (M=5.360 ± 0.131).
There was a significant effect of group, F(1,153)=4.832, p=0.029, η2p=0.031. Participants needed more time to give an answer in the social observation (M=5.713 ± 0.156) than in the control group (M=5.229 ± 0.155). 
The interaction between Response Type and Group was nonsignificant, F(1,153)=0.015, p=0.904, η2p<0.001. 
The interaction between Dilemma type and Response type was significant, F(1.816, 277.822)=70.220, p<0.001, η2p=0.315. For the response Appropriate participants showed longer reaction time in personal moral dilemmas (M=5.696 ± 0.241) vs Non-personal moral dilemmas (M=4.693 ± 0.131) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[0.446, 1.559]), but not vs. non-moral dilemmas (M=5.692 ± 0.117) (p=1.000, 95%CI=[-0.532, 0.539]). Moreover, it took longer to response Appropriate in non-moral dilemmas as compared to non-personal Moral Dilemmas (p<0.001, 95%CI=[0.743, 1.256]). For the response Inappropriate there was no difference in reaction time between personal moral dilemmas and non-personal moral dilemmas (p<0.192, 95%CI=[-0.458, 0.059]). However, it took longer to response Inappropriate in non-moral dilemmas (M=7.588 ± 0.227) as compared to personal moral dilemmas (M=4.479 ± 0.106) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[2.592, 3.626]) and non-personal moral dilemmas (M=4.678 ± 0.104) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[2.407, 3.413]).
The interaction between Dilemma type and Group was nonsignificant, F(1.759,153.00)=0.008, p=0.987, η2p<0.001. 
The tree-way interaction between Group, Answer and Dilemma Type was also nonsignificant, F(1.816, 277.822)=0.016, p=0.977, η2p<0.0001. 

Deviations from the preregistration: For reaction times in the lexical decision task, we have planned to delete raw reaction times below and above 3 standard deviations. Instead, we deleted mean reaction times below and above 3 standard deviations. 
We also deleted raw reaction times in the main task, which were below or above 3 standard deviations, which was not included in the preregistration. Mean reaction times were calculated without the outlying RTs.
Additional analyses (optional)

Lexical Decision Task
Hit rate
The average hit rate did not differ between groups, t(156)=-0.447, p=0.328.
2 (group) × 4 (word category) mixed ANOVA on hit rate revealed a significant main effect of word category, F(2.853,455.138)=19.753, p<0.001, η2p=0.112. Hit rate for Reputation words (M=0.934 ± 0.007) was lower as compared to Warmth words (M=0.955 ± 0.006) (p=0.038, 95%CI=[-0.042, -0.001]), but higher in comparison to Neutral words (M=0.891 ± 0.008) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[0.017, 0.065]). There was no difference between the Reputation words and Competence words (M=0.912 ± 0.008) (p=0.102, 95%CI=[-0.002, 0.044]). Hit rate for Competence words lower than for Warmth words (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-0.063, -0.022]), but there was no difference for Neutral words (p=0.218, 95%CI=[-0.005, 0.045]). Finally hit rate for Warmth words was higher than for Neutral words (p<0,001, 95%CI=[0.039, 0.087]). 
The simple effect for Group was not significant, F(1,156)=0.178, p=0.674, η2p=0.001
There was no significant interaction between the Group and Category, F(2.853, 455.138)=1.916, p=0.129, η2p=0.012. 
Reaction times
The average RTs did not differ between groups, t(153)=-0.473, p=0.318.
2 (group) × 4 (word category) mixed ANOVA on hit rate revealed a significant main effect of word category F(2.733,418.205)=46.774, p<0.001, η2p=0.234. Mean reaction time for Reputation words (M=502.691 ± 5.756) was lower than for Competence words (M=517.036 ± 6.058) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-23.971, -4.719]) and for Neutral words (M=535.637 ± 7.218) (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-44.061, -21.830]), but higher than for Warmth words (M=493.0.49 ± 5.367) (p=0.018, 95%CI=[1.101, 18.182]). Mean reaction time for Competence words was higher as compared to Warmth words (p<0.001, 95%CI=[14.734, 33.240]), but lower in comparison to Neutral words (p<0.001, 96%CI=[-29.606, -7.595]). Finally mean reaction time for Warmth words was lower than for Neutral words (p<0.001, 95%CI=[-54.135, -31.040]). 
The simple effect for Group was not significant, F(1,153)=0.127, p=0.772, η2p=0.001. 
There was no significant interaction between the Group and Category, F(2.733, 418.205)=0.262, p=0.835, η2p=0.002. 
Sample characteristics by group
Utilitarian and deontological reasoning
2 (group) x 2 (reasoning mode) mixed ANOVA revealed a significant effect of reasoning mode, F(1,157)=152.323, p<0.001, η2p=0.492, with stronger deontological (M=0.658 ± 0.016) than utilitarian reasoning (M=0.395 ± 0.014). The effect of group was not significant, F(1,157)=0.010, p=0.921, η2p<0.001. The interaction between group and reasoning mode was also not significant, F(1,157)=0.240, p=0.625, η2p=0.002. 
Mood and arousal
2 (group) x 2 (measurement) mixed ANOVA on mood revealed no significant simple effects: Measurement, F(1,154)=0.067, p=0.796, η2p <0.001; Group, F(1,154)=0.515, p=0.474, η2p=0.003. The interaction of Measurement and Group was also not significant, F(1,154)=2.315, p=0.130, η2p=0.015. 
2 (group) x 2 (measurement) mixed ANOVA on arousal revealed no significant main effects: Measurement, F(1,154)=0.871, p=0.352, η2p <0.006; group, F(1,154)=0.004, p=0.951, η2p<0.001. The interaction of Measurement and Group was also not significant F(1,154)=0.305, p=0.582, η2p=0.002. 
Questionnaires
Independent sample t-tests for questionnaires measures yielded no significant differences between the control and experimental group: IRI, t(156)=-0.564, p=0.284, Cohen’s d=0.534; NFCog, t(156)=-0.439, p=0.661, Cohen’s d=0.873; FNE, t(156)=0.543, p=0.294, Cohen’s d=0.833. 
